node.text:
AH!! I'm so excited to finally share that I have written a new book! 

Reach for the Stars 🌟 illustrated by the magical @honeej and published by @mackidsbooks 

Pre-order at the link in my bio!

I wrote Reach for the Stars in a sea of postpartum emotions a few months after my daughter was born. I would sit in my bed, hours on end, with my daughter sleeping next to me, and a computer in my lap. I cry-typed each page, trying to put into words all the things I hoped she would reach for throughout her life and all the things I hoped I could teach her along the way.

There are pieces of my soul in these pages and I truly hope you love it. 🌟

Pre-order should be available at your local bookstore (call to ask!) and is also available on Amazon.

node.text:
Some of the COOLEST things you’ll find at the Kennedy Space Center 🚀 @kennedyspacecenter 

“SLS” is NASA’s next big rocket (the Space Launch System). Construction is currently underway (you get to see parts of it in this video!). It’s the rocket designed to take humans back to the moon… and onto Mars. 

This video shows you where that rocket launches from, where it is currently being built and where the President will likely watch it as it launches the first woman to the moon. 🚀🙌🏼🌗

Here we are conducting a common Acid-Base Reaction.

What you need:
Baking Soda (any amount - let's say a few spoonfuls)
Lemon juice (or vinegar - about a couple spoonfuls)
Food coloring (optional, but is it really? because it makes this so pretty!) Acid Base reactions are everywhere, from acid rain to cookies. When they're mixed together they form water and a salt, and with baking soda we get those things + carbon dioxide! That's what makes this experiment so fun! #stayathomescience

node.text:
35 THOUSAND. I'm speechless.

Well, not really of course. I have a lot to say :)

Over 35,000 parents, educators, caretakers, and families signed this. It's hard to wrap my head around 35,000 individual people wanting this show enough to take the time to sign this petition (which I had nothing to do with, it’s completely fan-run!)

If you swipe you can read some of the comments on the petition. The reasons why they took the time to sign this. This was more than just a show to them, their family, and their kids - especially their daughters. Many families saw this show spark something new in their kids. For many girls - it was their first introduction to a woman in STEM that they could relate to.

If you'll forgive me, I'd like to hype up my show a bit. 

👶For one, kids loved it. That's the most important thing. It was fun and engaging and they binged watched it over and over again. 

👨‍👩‍👧Parents loved it. It's one of those kids shows that you actually don't mind watching with your child. In fact, many parents said that it gave them something to bond over with their kid. Ideas for activities to do together. Something exciting to talk together about. (plus, guilt-free screen time!)

🧑‍🔬And the scientific community loved it. The science checks out. Instead of oversimplifying science we leaned into the messiness of it all. We described the scientific process and encouraged kids to make their own hypotheses - and told them it was okay (wonderful even!) if their hypotheses were wrong. Science is all about trial and error after all. 

We didn't underestimate the intelligence of kids. We don't talk down to them. We give them the authority to be curious and explore on their own. 

This show changes the way girls view themselves and the way boys view girls/women. It is literally changing the image the future generation formulates in their minds when they envision "scientist." 

I'm so grateful to @Netflix for bringing this meaningful show to the world, and I'd love to keep working together to continue doing just that!!

Petition in bio. ☺️

node.text:
I’m giving away a @LEGO NASA Space Shuttle Discovery Set! #Ad 

Simply comment your favorite space emoji below and I’ll select someone at random on Friday to send this to (must be US-based). 

This set includes the Discovery Space Shuttle and the Hubble Space Telescope! 

The 300+ page building guide walks you through it step by step and even gives you fun facts about the spacecraft along the way. 

It’s a great project to build piece by piece as a family. My husband loves The LEGO Group and was sad that I only let him build a few bags of this one! 😊 

LEGO sets truly are for all ages! #LEGOPartner #GoBeyond @NASA

node.text:
To the fathers who inspire me. 

My father. My father who grew up in poverty in West Virginia. Who was the youngest of 4 and worked since he was 11 to buy the family their first car. Who worked at a coal company and was laid off bc of the dying industry and worked to find another job to support his family. Who helped (with my mom) to provide our family with everything we needed. Who would come home and help me with my homework and teach me *how* to learn. A self-made man who came from a single mother and the toughest of circumstances and persevered nonetheless. My dad. My inspiration to reach higher. 

My daughter’s father who is patient and loving and kind. Who sings and cuddles and dances with our little Rose. Who plans for and protects and feeds and cleans and kisses all the boo boos. 

I’m so lucky to have these men, these fathers in my life. They inspire me to be a better daughter, wife, mother, person.

Happy Father’s Day to the dads out there inspiring others, even when they don’t realize it. ❤️

UPDATE:
So many of you wanted to donate polos!!!! We ran completely out of them and now 75 polos are going to people who need a little help getting professional wear this summer!

Want a free polo?

It’s intern season which means many of you may need to find something ~professional~ looking for the next 10 weeks. 

Professional clothing is not usually the cheapest and not everyone can afford to purchase an entirely new wardrobe for the summer. 

SO - I’m giving 5 of my NASA polos away for free and marking it down 20% in my store.

If you’re having a hard time finding affordable professional clothing, please fill out the form in my bio. I’ll pick 5 people at random to send a free polo to. No other requirements. 

Polo is black with the NASA worm logo stitched in white. 100% cotton and ethically sourced. “Women’s-cut” and available in XS-XL (I’m wearing an XS). 

Happy interning!! 🌟

AH!! I'm so excited to finally share that I have written a new book! 

Reach for the Stars 🌟 illustrated by the magical @honeej and published by @mackidsbooks 

Pre-order at the link in my bio!

I wrote Reach for the Stars in a sea of postpartum emotions a few months after my daughter was born. I would sit in my bed, hours on end, with my daughter sleeping next to me, and a computer in my lap. I cry-typed each page, trying to put into words all the things I hoped she would reach for throughout her life and all the things I hoped I could teach her along the way.

There are pieces of my soul in these pages and I truly hope you love it. 🌟

Pre-order should be available at your local bookstore (call to ask!) and is also available on Amazon.

I’ve talked all about the science behind @Febreze AIR, but there's more! Let's talk about breathability.

It all comes down to particle size and you can breathe easier knowing Febreze scientists worked hard to design a formula with particles that are just the right size – small enough to stay in the air but large enough so you won't breathe it into your lungs. 

Febreze AIR's formula uses particles that are approximately 20x larger than a particle from an asthma inhaler. It's like comparing a marble to a beach ball! It's Air Care you can feel good about using it in your home.

Head to my link in bio to learn more about breathability and the science behind Febreze AIR. #FebrezePartner #FebrezeBehindTheBottle

node.text:
The beginning of US human Spaceflight. 

I’m standing in front of a Mercury-Redstone rocket (you’ll see this if you visit the Kennedy Space Center) - the rocket that brought the first American into space. 

These vehicles were originally ballistic missiles and were provided to NASA by the US Army. They had to be modified and go through various additional tests to human-rate it. 

One of those tests involved HAM, the chimpanzee who was launched into space in January 1961 and paved the way for Alan Shepard’s flight - the first American in space. 

HAM survived the journey - I’ll share a picture of him on my stories. His name is an acronym for the laboratory that prepared him for this historic flight (Holloman Aerospace Medical Center)

You may have heard that NASA had the Mercury, Gemini, and Apollo programs. Each of these programs were designed to do different things to prepare us to send humans to the moon. 

Mercury - the goal was to see if humans could survive a trip to space and back. 

Gemini - the goal was to test a long duration trip (up to 2 weeks) in space and its affect on humans, understand how to rendezvous and dock spacecraft in orbit, and to perfect reentry and landing methods. 

Apollo - well this one brought us to the moon and tested all the other components and procedures (like getting into lunar orbit and coming back home) required to bring humans to another planetary body for the first time in history. 

But it all started right here, with this missile…ahem, rocket. 🚀
